/*--------------------------------*- Choupo -*-----------------------*\
  Utility: grid electricity (the plant's electrical service).

  Sources:
    Turton et al., "Analysis, Synthesis and Design of Chemical Processes"
      5th ed., 2018, Table 8.3 (utility costs) -- electricity ~0.06-0.12
      USD/kWh industrial.
    Sinnott & Towler, "Chemical Engineering Design" 6th ed., 2022, §6.5
      (purchased electricity as the priciest utility per GJ).

  When to use:
    The electrical service that drives ROTATING equipment: pump and
    compressor MOTORS draw it; turbine GENERATORS (an electricLoad)
    feed it back.  The third utility tier alongside heating and
    cooling -- usually the most expensive per GJ delivered, which is
    why shaft work is not "free" and a plant's power bill belongs in
    the utilities report next to the steam and cooling-water bills.

  How it is tallied (utilityAllocation report, tier "power"):
    consumers  pump / compressor   grid draw = W_shaft / driveEfficiency
    producers  electricLoad        grid feed = W_electric (already net of
                                               the generator efficiency)
    A shaft work supplied by an energy WIRE (turbine -> compressor) is
    mechanical, NOT grid electricity, and is not counted.
\*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/

utility     electricity;
tier        power;
mechanism   electrical;

// 0.10 EUR/kWh industrial tariff = 0.10 / 3.6e-3 GJ = 27.8 EUR/GJ.
cost        27.8;                      // €/GJ delivered (drawn) / credited (fed)
costYear    2022;                      // reference price year

driveEfficiency 0.95;                  // electric motor / generator electromechanical eff.

description "Grid electricity for motors / generators (~0.10 EUR/kWh)";
